# Chirp injection for Twin Rotor Tailsitter actuator system-ID

## Context

We want a way to do **actuator system identification** on the twin-rotor tailsitter by
injecting a swept-frequency *chirp* directly into the control allocator, **bypassing the
multicopter attitude/rate controllers**. Normally `mc_att_control` → `mc_rate_control`
produce `vehicle_torque_setpoint` / `vehicle_thrust_setpoint`, which the control allocator
turns into actuator outputs. For system ID we instead want a clean, repeatable chirp to
drive one control axis at a time (with the rotors held at a fixed RPM) so we can measure the
open-loop actuator/airframe frequency response.

The single authoritative place to do this for this airframe is
`ActuatorEffectivenessTwinRotorTailsitter::updateSetpoint()`. For the twin-rotor tailsitter
the effectiveness *matrix* is all-zeros (motors & servos are added with empty axis vectors in
`getEffectivenessMatrix()`, lines 181‑197), so `updateSetpoint()` computes **every** motor and
servo output itself from the 6-axis `control_sp` (lines 202‑272). Injecting there gives full,
clean control of the outputs while reusing the existing swashplate/elevon geometry.

The five requested chirps map onto the axes that `updateSetpoint` already consumes:

| Requested chirp        | Inject into                              | Code reference |
|------------------------|------------------------------------------|----------------|
| Cyclic pitch (@6k rpm) | `control_sp(PITCH)` → symmetric cyclic   | `.cpp:239` |
| Cyclic yaw   (@6k rpm) | `control_sp(YAW)` → differential cyclic  | `.cpp:239` |
| Collective roll (@6k)  | `control_sp(ROLL)` → diff. collective    | `.cpp:240` |
| Collective             | `collective_pitch` term                  | `.cpp:219,240` |
| RPM                    | motor output `actuator_sp(0/1)` directly | `.cpp:218,222‑223` |

Because rotor RPM **and** collective both derive from `THRUST_Z` today (`.cpp:218‑219`), a clean
RPM chirp and a clean collective chirp must be decoupled: collective is chirped on the
`collective_pitch` term while the motor is held; RPM is chirped on the motor output while
collective/cyclic stay at baseline. During the cyclic/collective chirps the motors are held at a
settable command `CA_CHIRP_RPM` (the normalized motor value that equals ~6000 rpm on the
hardware), instead of going through the throttle curve.

## Chirp equation (confirmed)

Settable in YAML: `freq_init (f0)`, `freq_final (f1)`, `chirp_order (k)`, `total_time (T)`, plus `amp (A)`.
Running elapsed time `t` sweeps `0 → T`.

```
beta = (f1 - f0) / T^k                                   # T>0; k>=0  (T^0 = 1)
out  = A * sin( 2*pi * ( beta/(k+1) * t^(k+1) + f0 * t ) )
```

Instantaneous frequency `= beta*t^k + f0`, sweeping exactly `f0 → f1` over `T`.
`k = 1` is the textbook linear chirp. At `t = 0`, `out = 0` (smooth start).

## Design

**Bypass semantics:** when chirp mode is active the incoming `control_sp` (from the MC
controllers) is *replaced*, not added to — a local copy is zeroed and only the selected axis is
driven by the chirp. When chirp mode is off (`CA_CHIRP_MODE == 0`) behavior is byte-for-byte
unchanged.

**Timing / run mode (one-shot per arm):** chirp start time is captured on the first armed frame
after enabling; `t = (hrt_absolute_time() - start)/1e6`. When `t > T` the chirp output returns to
baseline (held RPM / trims). Disarming resets the start latch so the next arm replays the sweep.
A param change also resets the latch.

